{"cursor":"25969","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n{{Buddhist term\n| fontsize=100% title=Mindfulness pi= sati sa= smá¹ti (à¤¸à¥à¤®à¥à¤¤à¤¿) en=\n| mindfulness, awareness, inspection, recollection,\n| retention bo= à½à¾²à½à¼à½à¼ bo-Latn=Wylie: dran pa; THL: trenpa/drenpa zh=\n| nian, å¿µ vi= niá»m turkish= farkÄ±ndalÄ±k ja= ãã³ ja-Latn= nen ko=ì¼ ko-\n| Latn=yeom or yÅm\n}}\n\n'Mindfulness' (Pali: sati, Sanskrit: smá¹ti; also translated as\n'awareness') is a spiritual or psychological faculty ([[indriya]]) that,\naccording to the teaching of the Buddha, is considered to be of great importance\nin the path to enlightenment . It is one of the seven factors of enlightenment.\n\"Correct\" or \"right\" mindfulness (Pali: sammÄ-sati, Sanskrit samyak-smá¹ti) is\nthe seventh element of the noble eightfold path. Mindfulness meditation can also\nbe traced back to the earlier Upanishads, part of Hindu scripture. http://w-\nww.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/016383439500025M\n\nEnlightenment (bodhi) is a state of being in which greed, hatred and delusion\n(Pali: moha) have been overcome, abandoned and are absent from the mind.\nMindfulness, which, among other things, is an attentive awareness of the\nreality of things (especially of the present moment) is an antidote to\ndelusion and is considered as such a 'power' (Pali: bala). This faculty\nbecomes a power in particular when it is coupled with clear comprehension of\nwhatever is taking place.\n\nThe Buddha advocated that one should establish mindfulness ([[satipatthana]]) in\none's day-to-day life maintaining as much as possible a calm awareness of one's\nbodily functions, sensations (feelings), objects of consciousness (thoughts and\nperceptions), and consciousness itself. The practice of mindfulness supports\nanalysis resulting in the arising of wisdom (Pali: paÃ±Ã±Ä, Sanskrit:\n[[prajÃ±Ä]]). \"In short, the contemplative training known as âshamathaâ\n(meditative quiescence) deals with the development and refinement of attention;\nand this is the basis for âvipashyanaâ (contemplative insight), which entails\nmethods for experientially exploring the nature of the mind and its relation to\nthe world at large.\" from a description of the 18th Mind and Life Dialogues\nmeeting, official webpage, http://www.mindandlife.org/dialogues/past-\nconferences/ml18/ A key innovative teaching of the Buddha was that\nmeditative stabilisation must be combined with liberating\ndiscernment. Alexander Wynne, The origin of Buddhist meditation. Routledge,\n2007, page 73.\n\nThe Satipatthana Sutta (Sanskrit: Smá¹tyupasthÄna SÅ«tra) is an early text dealing\nwith mindfulness.\n\nMindfulness practice, inherited from the Buddhist tradition, is being employed\nin Western psychology to alleviate a variety of mental and physical conditions,\nincluding obsessive-compulsive disorder, anxiety, and in the prevention of\nrelapse in depression and drug\naddiction. http://scan.oxfordjournals.org/content/2/4/259.full See\nalso Mindfulness (psychology).\n","linknr":779,"url":"Mindfulness_(Buddhism)","recorded":1363414088,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Mindfulness&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Mindfulness&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Mindfulness","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bi